    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series. Then filter metric records to the incident window start=2024-01-23 06:50:39 UTC and end=2024-01-23 07:20:39 UTC (inclusive). Restrict analysis to these cmdb_id values only: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) produce: anomaly_count (points where value >= global P95; if global P95==0 treat value>0 as anomaly), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), latest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95 (use None or large number if global_p95==0). Also return: total metric records in-window for these five services and number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) (within these services) that have >=1 anomaly. Return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count descending." }

{
    "analysis": "We focused metric anomalies on the five candidate services and found multiple KPIs in ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service that exceeded their global P95 during the incident window. Most groups show anomaly_count=2 (two minutes) and some higher-severity deviations: ts-route-service/diskio (severity_ratio ≈ 3.77) and ts-order-service/latency-90 (severity_ratio ≈ 2.55). ts-train-service and ts-travel-service had no prominent anomalies in the previous summary. According to the workflow, we must now use traces to distinguish which of the faulty services is the most downstream faulty service in call-chains; traces will help pick the root-cause service among multiple service-level faults. We should also later inspect logs for the chosen candidate to identify the specific failure reason (resource type: CPU/memory/disk/io/socket/network).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series. Then filter trace records to the incident window start=2024-01-23 06:50:39 UTC and end=2024-01-23 07:20:39 UTC (inclusive). Restrict analysis to traces related to the candidate services: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service — include any trace rows where cmdb_id is one of those OR where trace_name mentions a target like 'to_ts-<service>' or 'from_ts-<service>' for those services. For each relevant (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: anomaly_count (value>=global P95; if global_p95==0 count value>0), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), latest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95 (use None or very large number if global_p95==0). Return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count descending. Also return total trace records in-window for these candidate-related traces and number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) groups with ≥1 anomaly." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found repeated anomalies involving auth, order and travel call paths. Notably, auth-related duration_p95 spikes (severity ≈ 1.45) and travel-related row_count/duration anomalies (highest counts) coexist with metric anomalies in ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level faults exist we must use traces to identify the most downstream faulty service in the call chain. The next step is to extract call-direction traces that target any of the five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) during the incident window, compute anomalies per caller->callee trace group (using global P95 from the full series), and list earliest anomaly times and severity — this will reveal which candidate service appears as the downstream faulty service within impacted call chains.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series. Then filter rows to the incident window start=2024-01-23 06:50:39 UTC and end=2024-01-23 07:20:39 UTC (inclusive). From the filtered set, select rows where trace_name contains 'to_ts-auth-service', 'to_ts-order-service', 'to_ts-route-service', 'to_ts-train-service', or 'to_ts-travel-service', or where trace_name contains 'from_ts-' followed by those service names. Group by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and for each group compute: anomaly_count (value >= global P95; if global_p95==0 count value>0), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95 (use None or a very large number if global_p95==0). Return up to top 50 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc. Also return the distinct list of caller cmdb_id -> callee service extracted from trace_name for these groups." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis showed repeated anomalies involving auth, order and travel flows. The strongest trace-level severity was for auth (trace.to_ts-auth-service.duration_p95 with severity ≈1.45). Metric anomalies were present in ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service (notably ts-route-service/diskio severity ≈3.77 and ts-order-service/latency-90 severity ≈2.55). According to the localization rules, we must use traces to determine which faulty service is the most downstream within impacted call-chains. The next actionable step is to build a compact caller→callee anomaly mapping for traces targeting any of the five candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service), and cross-check whether each callee service had metric anomalies within the incident window. This will show which candidate service is the downstream faulty service in the observed call paths and whether its own metrics were anomalous.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and metric.csv. Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) and per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series. Filter both datasets to the incident window start=2024-01-23 06:50:39 UTC and end=2024-01-23 07:20:39 UTC (inclusive). From the filtered trace rows, extract caller = cmdb_id and callee service name when trace_name contains the pattern 'to_ts-<service>' or 'from_ts-<service>' (map the <service> token to its canonical form like 'auth-service','order-service','route-service','train-service','travel-service'); keep only rows where callee is one of the five candidate services. For each caller→callee pair compute: anomaly_count (trace value >= global P95; if global P95==0 treat value>0 as anomaly), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), latest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window/global_p95 (handle global_p95==0 gracefully). Also, for each callee service include a boolean metric_anomaly_flag indicating whether metric.csv (filtered to the window) contained any KPI for that callee with an anomaly (value >= that KPI's global P95, or >0 when global_p95==0). Return up to top 50 caller→callee rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then severity_ratio desc. Also return the distinct list of callees (from the five candidates) that have metric_anomaly_flag==True." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed global thresholds and found multiple metric and trace anomalies across the five candidate services. Caller→callee aggregation shows repeated anomalies for order-service (many caller→order traces), auth-service (many caller→auth traces), and travel flows. All five candidate services have at least one metric KPI anomaly during the incident window. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level faults exist we must use traces to find the most-downstream faulty service within call chains. To decide the downstream faulty service we need a compact, time-ordered list of trace anomaly events (caller, callee, timestamp, severity) for 'to_ts-*' and 'from_ts-*' trace names targeting the five candidate services so we can observe call sequences and identify downstream faulty nodes.",
